      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How to Check a Brisbane Real Estate Agent's References Before Signing the Form 6
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Agent appraisals are sales presentations. References are the only independent verification you have. Here is exactly who to call, what to ask, and what to listen for before you sign a Form 6.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The Form 6 is the binding appointment that locks you in with a Brisbane real estate agent for a defined period. Once it is signed, you have committed to that agent for weeks or months, and your ability to swap agents mid-campaign is constrained by contract terms, advertising costs already spent, and the practical disruption of restarting. The single most under-used quality control step in the agent selection process is calling the agent's recent seller references before that signature happens. Thirty minutes of phone calls is one of the highest-ROI activities in the entire selling process, and almost no seller does it properly.</p>

      <p>The reason references matter is structural. An appraisal meeting is a sales presentation. The agent has prepared, walks you through their recent results, shows you their marketing material, and arrives with a proposed price range and a strategy. Everything you see is curated. References are the only independent verification you have that the claims and the experience hold up in practice, with people who have already been through a campaign with that agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why agent appraisals are not enough on their own</h2>
      <p>The standard agent pitch has a few predictable flaws that any seller should be alert to. Agents emphasise their best results and quietly omit the underperformers. The claimed average sale price often combines volume periods and outliers that are not representative of the everyday campaign. Track records can include team sales rather than personally managed listings, where the agent you are meeting was one of several names attached but not the primary point of contact through the campaign. None of these are necessarily dishonest, but each can leave you with a more flattering picture of the agent's performance than a balanced view would produce.</p>

      <p>References cut through this. A recent seller has lived through the full campaign, saw how the agent communicated when things were easy and when they were hard, knows whether the price guidance was accurate, and can tell you whether they would use the same agent again. Their answer carries weight that no appraisal slide deck can match.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ask the agent for</h2>
      <p>Ask for the names and contact details of three sellers in your suburb whose properties were sold by that agent in the last twelve months. Three is the minimum useful sample. Ideally the mix should include a strong sale (where the result exceeded expectations), an average sale (a routine campaign at expected price), and one that did not go as well (a longer days-on-market, a price reduction, or a campaign that did not produce the result the seller wanted). The agent who only offers strong sales as references is selecting for survivorship bias and you are not getting a full view.</p>

      <p>If the agent hesitates, deflects, or offers reasons why references cannot be provided, treat that as a meaningful signal. Reputable agents who have run quality campaigns are happy to refer you to recent sellers, often without prompting, because they know their references will close the appointment for them.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ask the references: opening</h2>
      <p>Open with questions that establish accuracy of the agent's price guidance and expectation setting. What was the agent's initial price guidance for the property, and how did the actual result compare? Did the agent help you set realistic expectations from the start, or did the price guide drift down through the campaign? Was the final result roughly in the range originally quoted, materially above, or materially below?</p>

      <p>Accuracy of the initial guidance is one of the most diagnostic questions you can ask. Agents who quote optimistically to win the listing and then talk vendors into reductions later show up in this question every time.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ask the references: process</h2>
      <p>Move next to questions about the campaign experience. How often did the agent communicate with you during the campaign, and was the contact useful or perfunctory? How did the agent respond when something went wrong, for example a buyer pulling out, an open home with low attendance, or a contract falling over after exchange? Did the agent recommend specific presentation improvements before launch, and were those recommendations supported by reasoning rather than by feel?</p>

      <p>Process questions reveal the texture of working with the agent across a six to ten week campaign. The right agent communicates honestly when things are going well and harder when things are not. References will tell you the difference.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ask the references: outcome</h2>
      <p>Close with the outcome questions. Did you feel the agent fought for your highest possible price in negotiation, or did they push you toward acceptance early to close a deal? Did the agent handle negotiations well in the room, when offers were under pressure and counter-offers were live? Would you use the same agent again, and why or why not? The last question is the most diagnostic of all: a reference who hesitates before answering, or who answers with caveats, is telling you more than a reference who says "absolutely" without thinking.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to listen for in the answers</h2>
      <p>Strong references give specific examples rather than vague endorsements. Look for mentions of a particular open home, a specific negotiation, a turning point in the campaign, a moment when the agent's communication mattered. Specifics are signs that the relationship was real and the campaign was actively managed. Look for consistent praise across multiple references on a small set of recurring themes: communication, negotiation, honesty, market knowledge. If the same strengths come up from three independent sellers, that is a signal. Look for honest acknowledgement of any campaign challenges. References who say "the campaign was perfect" with no qualifications are usually overstating, because almost no campaign runs without any friction.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to be wary of</h2>
      <p>A few patterns should put you on alert. Vague endorsements ("they were great", "no complaints") with no specifics often mean the seller is being polite rather than enthusiastic. References that all come from the same year and the same property type may indicate the agent is selective about who they put forward. A reference who turns out to be a friend or family member is not independent and should be discounted heavily. Most importantly, if the agent refuses to provide references at all, walk away. Reputable Brisbane agents have happy recent sellers and will provide their details on request.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The public data sanity check</h2>
      <p>Before or after the calls, cross-check the references' sale outcomes against realestate.com.au and domain.com.au sold sections. The sale price, suburb, sale date, and sometimes the campaign duration are public. Make sure the prices and timing match what the references describe in their answers. This step verifies the references are real, that the agent did genuinely manage those sales, and that the seller's recollection lines up with the public record. Discrepancies are rare but informative when they appear.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The questions you should NOT ask</h2>
      <p>Avoid leading questions that prompt the answer you want to hear. "They were good, right?" tells the reference what response is expected and you learn nothing. Ask open questions ("how did the agent handle X?") and let the reference answer in their own words. Do not ask for confidential information about the buyer, financial details, or anything that would put the reference in an awkward position. Do not pressure the reference to share details they are not comfortable with. The point is to gather honest signal, not to extract information.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The second-stage check</h2>
      <p>If the references are positive, finish with a quick scan of the agent's RateMyAgent reviews and Google reviews. Look for patterns rather than individual reviews. Single bad reviews are noise; almost every active agent will have one or two unhappy clients in their history. Patterns are signals. If multiple reviews mention poor communication, missed deadlines, or pressure tactics, that pattern matters even if the references you spoke to were positive. Conversely, a strong overall review profile reinforces the impression you formed from the references.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Thirty minutes of phone calls before signing the Form 6 is one of the highest-ROI activities in the entire selling process. The cost of getting the agent decision wrong on a Brisbane inner-east sale is regularly twenty to a hundred thousand dollars on the final price, plus weeks of additional campaign time and materially more stress. The cost of doing the reference checks properly is a few short calls, scheduled around the agent appointment process. Do this work before the signature, not after. After signing, you have committed, and the chance to gather independent signal is gone. Before signing, you have leverage, choices, and the time to ask the questions that will tell you whether this is the right agent for your campaign.</p>

